      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Even if the brake pads seem to have some meat on them, the high-pitched squeal could still be caused by other factors. One possibility is that the brake rotors are warped or excessively worn, causing the brake pads to vibrate and produce the squeal. \n\nIt's also possible that the brake caliper is loose or has a problem with the brake hose, which could cause the noise. However, you mentioned the noise is coming from the passenger side, which makes it less likely to be a caliper issue. \n\nAnother possibility is that the ABS (Anti-Lock Braking System) sensor on the front passenger side is malfunctioning, which could cause the noise. The ABS sensor is responsible for monitoring the speed of each wheel and adjusting the brake pressure accordingly. If the sensor is faulty, it could cause the brake system to vibrate and produce a squeal. \n\nIt's worth noting that some modern vehicles, like your 2018 Camry, have a brake pad wear sensor that can trigger a warning light on the dashboard if the pads are worn down too much. However, this sensor is usually not the cause of a high-pitched squeal. \n\nTo get to the bottom of the issue, I would recommend having",
